erican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cheshire): probably a variant of the Suffolk surname <b>Naunton</b>, a habitational name from Naunton Hall in Rendlesham and possibly also Naughton (both in Suffolk). The latter may derive from the Old Norse personal name <i>Nagli</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":75,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Nanton was born in 1380, in England. He had at least 2 sons with Anne Tymperley. He died in 1462, at the age of 82."},"et":{"1380–1462":"1380–1462","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1410–1490":"1410–1490","–Male":"Surnud","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1462":"1462","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1490":"1490","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1380–1462":"1380–1462","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1410–1490":"1410–1490","–Male":"Kuollut","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1462":"1462","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1490":"1490","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1380–1462":"1380–1462","1385–Female":"1385–Décédée","1410–1490":"1410–1490","–Male":"Décédé","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1462":"1462","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1490":"1490","England":"Angleterre","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert de Nanton est né en 1380, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 2 fils avec Anne Tymperley. Il est décédé en 1462, à l’âge de 82 ans."},"de":{"1380–1462":"1380–1462","1385–Female":"1385–Verstorben","1410–1490":"1410–1490","–Male":"Verstorben","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1462":"1462","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1490":"1490","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","lifeSummary":"Robert de Nanton wurde 1380 in England geboren. Er hatte mit Anne Tymperley mindestens 2 Söhne. Er starb 1462 im Alter von 82 Jahren."},"ht":{"1380–1462":"1380–1462","1385–Female":"1385–Desede","1410–1490":"1410–1490","–Male":"Desede","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1462":"1